        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We request a frequency set-up allowing us to cover the CO(2-1) line with a 1875 MHz baseband (1631 km/s) and a raw spectral resolution of 0.976 MHz (~1.27 km/s). This covers the entire velocity width expected, including any high-velocity gas detected around the SMBH. The velocity gradient in the centre of this source is 40 km/s. In order to detect the kinematic signature of the SMBH we require channels finer than this. We adopt 10 km/s as our canonical resolution here, as this is roughly the expected velocity dispersion. We retain the ability to bin more if the signal to noise is low, or unbin to obtain higher precision measurements of the molecular gas kinematics in bright regions, to reach an optimal compromise between spectral resolution and S/N (and minimise the uncertainty on the derived SMBH mass).

We also include three continuum spectral windows, to accurately measure and remove any continuum emission present.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>As discussed in the proposal, the expected SOI of the small SMBH in this object is ~0.13". In order to be sensitive to an SMBH of this size, and provide a better constraint on its mass than previous studies, we propose to marginally resolve this sphere of influence, with a resolution of 0.1".  This will be enough to clearly separate the SMBH kinematic signature from that of the bulk of the stars given the proposed velocity resolution and signal-to-noise ratio. We will analyze the data at higher resolution by adjusting the weighting in post-processing if there is sufficient signal near the nucleus in order to make an even more precise measurement.

We propose to map this object using the CO(2-1) line (Band 6), for which the flux is known. One can reach the required resolution in this band using array configuration C36-6. The largest angular scale visible in this array configuration is larger than the total extent of the molecular disk in each channel (see Fig. 2), and hence we do not expect to resolve out flux. If, however, a larger component is present, we would expect it to break into individual GMCs, again giving us the ability to retain the majority of the flux. </prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>This galaxy has CO(2-1) single-dish observations of the very central region, published in Boeker et al., 2011. From these single dish observations we know the line flux density (14.25 mJy), and line width (40 km/s) in the centre. We estimate the size of the molecular gas reservoir using our integral-field unit observations which reveal a rotating disk of H2 in the centre of this object, with an extent of ~1". Experience shows that the emission is normally only spatially resolved in one direction (tracing the ``spider'' diagram) in individual velocity channels. We thus take the number of synthesised beams across the source in each channel as the ratio of the minor-axis length (~0.5"; see Fig. 2) to the synthesised beam size (0.1"; justified below).
We assume the observed flux per channel is split between these beams, giving us the expected surface brightness per beam we need to reach in these observations (14.25 mJy/5 = 2.85 mJy). Requiring a detection of this emission at a signal to noise of 5 leads to the requested RMS of 0.57mJy. 

The uncertainty on the kinematic modelling we will conduct varies directly with the channel width. The velocity gradient in the centre of this source is 40 km/s. In order to detect the kinematic signature of the SMBH we require channels finer than this. We adopt 10 km/s as our canonical resolution here, as this is roughly the expected velocity dispersion, but retain the ability to unbin to obtain higher precision measurements of the molecular gas kinematics in bright regions. </prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
